<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>BASICS: ENERGY</h1>

        <h2>BASIC 1</h2>
        <p>Individuals are protected against electrocution and fire. Devices are protected against fire, power stability, and effects of lightning.</p>

        <h3>Best Practices</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>All live cables must be inaccessible.</li>
            <li>Generators must be grounded.</li>
            <li>All sockets must be grounded.</li>
            <li>300-mA RCD protection on general circuits.</li>
            <li>30-mA RCD protection on final circuits.</li>
            <li>Properly scaled MCBs and electrical wires.</li>
            <li>ABC type fire extinguisher near distribution boards and generators.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>BASIC 2</h2>
        <p>Services are protected against power failures and interruptions.</p>

        <h3>Best Practices</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Protect sensitive equipment from voltage variations.</li>
            <li>Backup systems (UPS) in critical zones.</li>
            <li>Regular power assessments and consumption checks.</li>
            <li>Properly scaled generators and UPS systems.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Monitoring</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Facilities inspected every 6-18 months.</li>
            <li>Power requirement assessments every 6 months.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Benefits</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Protection against electrocution and fires.</li>
            <li>Continuity of medical and non-medical activities.</li>
            <li>Equipment remains undamaged.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Common Mistakes</h2>
        <div class="highlight">
            <ul>
                <li>Unprotected spliced connections.</li>
                <li>No junction boxes.</li>
                <li>Improper or missing grounding.</li>
                <li>Exposed live wires.</li>
                <li>Unbalanced 3-phase generator loads.</li>
                <li>Oversized or insufficient protection devices.</li>
                <li>No maintenance plan in place.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>Roles & Responsibilities</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Logistics ensures safe installations.</li>
            <li>Qualified electricians must assess and conduct work.</li>
            <li>Ensure continuity of power services and backups.</li>
            <li>Train new electricians according to standards.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Necessary Resources</h2>

        <h3>Time</h3>
        <p>Assessment (~1 week), design (~1 week), procurement (1 week to 3 months). Bringing a 100mÂ² facility to standard takes 10-25 days.</p>

        <h3>Supply</h3>
        <p>Local suppliers must be validated. International purchase is recommended if quality is uncertain. Watch out for counterfeit items!</p>

        <h3>HR (Human Resources)</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Level 9 - Energy Manager:</b> Manages large projects.</li>
            <li><b>Level 8 - Energy Specialist:</b> Controls electrical installations.</li>
            <li><b>Level 5 - Electrician:</b> Maintains and repairs installations.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Equipment</h3>
        <p>Essential tools: RCD, RCD tester, wire gauge, voltmeter, junction boxes, connectors, circuit breakers, grounding rods, UPS systems.</p>
    </div>
